</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="74" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="74">
Argentina. Tierra del Fuego: Dpto. Ushuaia, Estancia Moat, on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Winteraceae" genus="Drimys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Drimys winteri" order="Canellales" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="winteri">Drimys winteri</taxonomicName>
, 21 Mar 1998, M. Rajchenberg 11370 (holotype: BAFC [50038], by original designation).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="74">
For a detailed description and illustration, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Greslebin, AG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="18" pageNumber="83" pagination="1155 - 1165" title="The genus Hyphodontia in the Patagonian Andes forests of Argentina." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/3761483" volume="92" year="2000">Greslebin and Rajchenberg (2000)</bibRefCitation>
. The authors compared the new species with 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Schizoporaceae" genus="Xylodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Xylodon detriticus" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="detriticus">Xylodon detriticus</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Schizoporaceae" genus="Hyphodontia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hyphodontia detritica" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="detritica">Hyphodontia detritica</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Meruliaceae" genus="Hypochnicium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hypochnicium rickii" order="Polyporales" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="rickii">Hypochnicium rickii</taxonomicName>
. Our investigation of authentic material confirms the morphological similarity amongst these three species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
